# linux 
- kernel : cpu, ram, network driver,..
- userspace : /bin, bash,  ls, cat, cp, apt, ... 

# docker 
- same kernel with host
- different userspace 

# a docker image 
build on userspace

# example Dockerfile
cat <<EOF> Dockerfile
FROM alpine:3.20
CMD ["echo", "Hello from my first Docker image!"]
EOF

docker build -t my-hello .

docker run --rm my-hello


-----
# docker network 
- brigde network (default): 172.17.0.x , private in host, container in this network can connect to each other, can not connect to other host
- host network : container uses the same host ip, if container run app on port 80, this is actually host port
- overlay network : a network across multiple physical host, container in host A can connect to container in host B
- None network: 127.0.0.1 . security batch job, data processing scripts, secret rotation



